## Migration: `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationToken` + `Task`

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on .NET Core/5+. `ThreadAbortException` is obsolete. The entire cooperative-cancellation model replaces forced thread termination.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run uses the ThreadPool instead of raw Thread creation
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // AggregateException from Task.Run is unwrapped by GetAwaiter().GetResult(),
        // so the original exception propagates directly — no manual wrapping needed.
    }
}
```

### If you can't change the caller signature

When `work` doesn't accept a `CancellationToken` (legacy compatibility):

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(work, token);

    try
    {
        // token only prevents scheduling; it won't interrupt running work
        if (task.Wait(timeout))
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();

        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
    catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
    {
        // Unwrap single-exception AggregateException to match original behavior
        throw ex.InnerException!;
    }
}
// ⚠️  WARNING: The work delegate keeps running after timeout — it is NOT killed.
//    This is the fundamental behavioral difference from Thread.Abort().
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Fire-and-forget on timeout** | Without cooperative cancellation, the work **keeps running** after you stop waiting. There is no safe .NET 8 equivalent to `Thread.Abort()`. |
| **`CancellationToken` must be checked** | The delegate must call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or check `token.IsCancellationRequested` at logical checkpoints — cancellation is cooperative. |
| **`Task.Run` vs `new Thread`** | `Task.Run` uses the ThreadPool. Long-blocking work can starve the pool. For CPU-heavy/long work, use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`. |
| **Exception unwrapping changed** | `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` unwraps `AggregateException`; `.Result` does not. Choose deliberately. |
| **`ThreadAbortException` catch blocks** | Delete them entirely — they'll never fire. If other code catches `ThreadAbortException`, replace with `OperationCanceledException`. |
| **Reentrancy / shared state** | `Thread.Abort()` could leave locks held and state corrupted. Cooperative cancellation is *safer*, but you must ensure cleanup in `finally` blocks. |

### Caller Migration Example

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After (.NET 8) — pass token into the actual I/O
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),  // use ct with DbCommand, HttpClient, etc.
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**Bottom line:** The signature-compatible shim works as a stopgap, but true migration requires threading `CancellationToken` through to the actual I/O — that's the only way to actually *stop* the work on timeout.
